The optical properties of N-BCDs under various harsh conditions have also been studied. The FL intensity of N-BCDs preserve ~88% of the initial intensity under continuous UV irradiation for 120 min (λ
                        ex = 365 nm) (Fig. S5b). Besides, the FL intensity of N-BCDs keeps extremely stable under broad pH ranges (pH 2.0–10.0), relative high ionic strengths (up to 2 M NaCl) as well as different temperatures (25–70 °C) (Figs. 2d, e, S5c). These results indicate the superior physiological stability of N-BCDs for further use. The cytotoxicity of N-BCDs has also been investigated by standard MTT assay. As shown in Fig. 2f, >85% cells keep survival after incubating with different concentrations of N-BCDs for 48 h, indicating the negligible cytotoxicity of N-BCDs. Besides, the N-BCDs are very small (2.54 ± 0.48 nm), thus could be removed by the organisms system. Then we also found that N-BCDs could enter into the both human cervical cancer cells (HeLa) and human gastric normal cells (GES-1) within 5 h and both displayed intense blue emission with 405 nm laser excitation by laser scanning confocal microscope (Fig. 3
                        ). All of these cells with the incubation of N-BCDs maintain their normal cellular morphology, further suggesting the low cytotoxicity and the feasibility of N-BCDs using as bioimaging agent. Moreover, the excellent biocompatibility also warrants the potential of N-BCDs as new nanomaterial inhibitors for HI aggregation process.
